n%20art%20and%20design%20student%20from%20France%2C%20had%20come%20to%20India%20in%20the%201990s%20for%20her%20diploma%20project%20as%20part%20of%20her%20final%20year%20assignment%20of%20art%20school.%20She%20started%20coming%20to%20India%20to%20work%20with%20various%20non-profit%20organisations%20to%20train%20Indian%20artisans%20in%20making%20products%20that%20could%20be%20sold%20in%20the%20international%20market.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EShe%20permanently%20settled%20in%20India%20in%202006%20after%20her%20marriage%20to%20Bishwadeep%2C%20a%20former%20journalist%2C%20whom%20she%20met%20at%20a%20yoga%20centre.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIris%20continued%20to%20work%20as%20a%20design%20consultant%20with%20international%20clothing%20brands.%20That%E2%80%99s%20when%20she%20was%20struck%20by%20the%20massive%20amounts%20of%20fabric%20waste%20generated%20by%20the%20fashion%20industry%20in%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CShe%20used%20to%20visit%20many%20of%20these%20factories%20in%20Delhi%2C%20which%20is%20a%20big%20production%20hub%20for%20many%20international%20fashion%20brands.%20She%20discovered%20that%20fabric%20waste%20is%20discarded%20in%20extreme%20bulk%20quantities.%20It%20was%20here%20that%20she%20was%20struck%20with%20the%20idea%20to%20use%20the%20scraps%20for%20making%20a%20useful%20product%2C%E2%80%9D%20shares%20Bishwadeep.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CAs%20she%20was%20already%20training%20artisan%20groups%2C%20she%20came%20across%20a%20marginalised%20group%20of%20Afghan%20refugee%20women.%20The%20refugee%20issue%20was%20close%20to%20her%20heart.%20We%20thought%20that%20this%20could%20be%20a%20good%20idea%20as%20it%20was%20difficult%20for%20us%20also%20to%20tap%20into%20the%20talents%20of%20artisans%20who%20live%20in%20far%20off%20tribal%20villages.%20We%20decided%20to%20marry%20both%20the%20concepts%20of%20upcycling%20fabric%20waste%20and%20generating%20employment%20for%20refugee%20women%2C%E2%80%9D%20he%20adds.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20a%20bid%20to%20do%20something